I"<p>CGP Grey has a great video about New Year’s resolutions and why they don’t work. Instead, he suggests that we use a theme. For example, someone who wants to improve their education might have a theme of learning. This is broad enough to keep you on track but not shackle you to something like a resolution such as “I will read 2 books a month.” That goal is easy to fail and hard to get back on track once you do. With a theme, you have a guiding light to pull you towards where you want to be. Most actions that you take should have a moment of consideration: “Will this take me closer to X theme?” If the answer is yes, you should do it, and if no, you should consider whether it is worth the other benefits.</p>

